Emotional Machine Funk2025 has been defined by the collapse of techno optimism. Where the nascent internet's frontier spirit once pointed to a bright future, today that promise feels sinister, curdled

Emotional Machine Funk2025 has been defined by the collapse of techno optimism. Where the nascent internet's frontier spirit once pointed to a bright future, today that promise feels sinister, curdled by the "corporate gloom" and data extraction documented in Liz Pelly's excellent book, Mood Machine. The year's most compelling machine funk reflects this irradiated state of distress on a personal and collective level, as well as caution about what our technological destiny truly holds.The electro, techno and slanted IDM we listened to in 2025 went beyond techno pessimism to focus on other knotty concepts, such as grief and loss, provoking visceral gut punches to attain those physical highs. It's music that makes you feel and move, which, if you go back to Detroit techno's history, has always been there. No one told this story better than the Motor City's early pioneers, whose fragile and furious proto-techno output was never blindly optimistic. RA's staff picks of the year pull from this DNA: DJ Bone's The End Of Never, with its muscular electro, stands as the embodiment of Detroit, rooted in a '90s urban reality that focused on interrogating systems of power and decay.These ghosts of past motifs echo through these releases, which are neither hopeful nor nostalgic throwbacks. This is machine music deeply rooted in the turmoil of the present, asserting that the sound of the zeitgeist refuses to be background noise. It's a defiant new link in a chain of creation that speaks to adversity, and it demands that we listen. What does that say about 2025, that artists are trying to produce music that says something through bleeps and bloops again?– Chloe LulaRecord of the YearBlawanSickElixirAfter more than a decade at the forefront of club music, Blawan could easily have settled into legacy act territory, churning out formulaic imitations of past successes from the comfort of the techno assembly line. Instead, on SickElixir, he doubles down on innovation.The album finds the UK artist at his most vulnerable. Themes of grief, trauma and addiction (he recently spoke to Crack about having to leave Berlin after drugs "basically shattered" his life there) are folded into serrated rhythms and monstrous, almost bodily vocal work—even fleeting moments of warmth arrive refracted through a darker lens. The ferocity of his early work remains, yet the melodic smears, fragmented vocal gasps and unexpectedly tender swells reflect an artist intent on expanding his emotional bandwidth. SickElixir sees Blawan turn years of experience into something raw and profound.– Michael LawsonRead the full reviewListen:BandcampRecordsMarie DavidsonCity Of ClownsIn a world shackled by surveillance capitalism, Marie Davidson posits what might be the only true subversion left: satirising this power structure with sexual hedonism run rampant. City Of Clowns brings this madcap concept to life. Thunderous, funky basslines and mind-melting electro synths are helmed by Davidson, who plays the Alexa-like narrator gone rogue, extolling the virtues of data mining with expletives and double entendres. If the machinist future our tech overlords are envisioning is even one tenth as sexy as this, bring on the singularity.– Jake IndianaRead the full reviewListen:BandcampUnspecified EnemiesRomance in the Age of Adaptive FeedbackPart of the enduring magic of '90s Detroit-school techno is how the producers made pieces of hardware sing. Louis Digital isn't from Detroit and it isn't the mid-90s, but you can't tell by listening to Romance in the Age of Adaptive Feedback. Equal parts nostalgic and futuristic, brimming with feeling and assembly-line grooves, the record is a pitch-perfect homage to classic Motor City techno and electro by a true lover of the form.– Henry IvryRead the full reviewListen:BandcampTracksDJ Bone"Deep Inside"On "Deep Inside," DJ Bone pairs his famously surgical drumwork with a simple vocal mantra, a reminder that there's a human pulse driving the circuitry. As the oscillating synths kick in, elastic and almost overcooked, the track feels like a machine learning its purpose, pushed by a human hand that refuses to let the gears lock into place. The way he flares open the mix turns his tight grid into something that emulates a living, breathing organism.– Reid BGRead the full reviewListen:BandcampSandwell District"Hidden"Austere techno brutalism be damned—on End Beginnings highlight, "Hidden," Regis and Function returned to their Sandwell District project with a rounded melodic sound that found its pocket and leaned deep into it. The track's interplay between insistent acid, throbbing mono synth bass and syncopated sub rumble displays a funkiness more readily associated with Motor City titans. "Hidden" evokes the shadowy, emotive pulse of Carl Craig classic "Sandstorms" while giving it the Sandwell District pressure-cooker treatment.– Oli WarwickRead the full reviewListen:BandcampMixLimited NetworkITPS119 LIMITED NETWORKAs Limited Network, Detroit-based artist Max Watts channels the city's lineage, using the TB-303 to connect classic machine funk with its sleek 2020s mutation. His Ilian Tape mix opens with tight 303 sequences: clean resonance peaks, controlled envelopes and a filter sweep that traces a line from forebears like Robert Hood and Jeff Mills. Rather than treat acid as nostalgia, the mix unfolds with curiosity, moving through Drexciya-esque passages and punchy electro workouts. Watts honours Detroit's foundations while showing how the machine-funk blueprint still resonates today.– Bella AquilinaListen:SoundCloudFurther ListeningPolygonia, Wata IgarashiCross PassageListen:BandcampBlack SitesR4Listen:BandcampEhua"Aria"Listen:BandcampBarker"Stochastic Drift"Read the reviewListen:BandcampTraxxThe Definitive Articles of House Music Chapter 6Listen:SoundCloudListen to the Emotional Machine Funk playlistSpotify

Bass WeightWe should've clocked it when FWD>> and Tempa returned. From late 2024 through 2025, bass weight has been pushed into new places. From Bristol outlet Dimeshift, which continues to lead fresh

Bass WeightWe should've clocked it when FWD>> and Tempa returned. From late 2024 through 2025, bass weight has been pushed into new places. From Bristol outlet Dimeshift, which continues to lead fresh, first wave-inspired dubstep, to Beatrice M., who released a strong run of their own tunes, as well as issuing music from the likes of Tighe, Old Man Crane and Dangermami via their label, Bait.Across the board, artists increasingly unified the roots of sound system music with their own astute, modern twists, propelled by a more femme-led, internationally reaching school of artists and labels. Introspekt's Moving the Center unlocked a newfound sensuality in dubstep and dark garage; tracks like Mia Koden's "Skank Steady" bottled anticipation for summer with floating keys and a warm bassline; Lauren Duffus's excellent Can's Gone Warm EP served weighty alt-pop, folding in trip-hop and post-dubstep shimmer reminiscent of Kelela's Cut 4 Me. And then Tracey & Riko Dan's "Sex Life" abandoned elegance entirely, taking a thrumming low-end and plonking a pithy hook on top: "All I wanna do is fuck, fuck, fuck, fuck, fuck."Alongside Beatrice M., names like EMA were busy earning much-deserved flowers with standout festival sets, while legends assembled in the form of Mala and dub techno veteran Paul St. Hilaire, who collaborated on "Like It's Always Been," the opening track on St. Hilaire's album. In a year that Timedance and SPE:C turned ten (and Tectonic hit 20), techno-infused bass weight stocks are arguably at an all-time high, and sound system music at large is, in all senses of the word, booming.– Nathan EvansRecord of the YearPaul St. Hilairew/ the ProducersFor Kynant Records' Richard Akingbehin and the voice of dub techno, Paul St. Hilaire, the decision to summon the ghost of Rhythm & Sound's seminal 2003 album, w/ the Artists, was classy yet bold. Would w/ the Producers build on its source material? Or risk living in its shadow? The album's faultless cast of collaborators, including Batu, Shinichi Atobe and Azu Tiwaline, made failure impossible. As a sonic aesthetic, dubwise is flourishing right now, and this LP bottles its power and beauty in myriad tones and tempos, from Mala's orchestral skank on "Like It's Always Been" to the slo-mo psych thump of Aurora Halal & DJ G's "Mary Jane Greenfield." The pièce de résistance is, of course, St. Hilaire himself. He graces every beat with poise and purpose, never overdoing it. As the years roll by, once-mythic musicians can lose touch with their former brilliance. Not this Dominican dub poet.– Carlos HawthornRead the full reviewListen:BandcampRecordsIntrospektMoving The CenterIntrospekt has what you want and what you need. Sound familiar? You might recognise those words from KMA Productions' '96 garage track "Cape Fear," which Introspekt samples on "Subliminate," the final track on her debut album. From the New York-based artist, what we want is something new, fresh and stimulating in a way we've not experienced before. And what we need is dubstep. Introspekt delivers both, making bass-heavy 140 riddims sound smoother and sexier than ever.– Sam DaviesRead the full reviewListen:Bandcampex_libris001 & 002Every time Dave Huismans returns, it's cause for celebration. Just one catch: the lexicon of writers and fans alike falls short in capturing his aversion to fixed form. What exactly is ex_libris? Iridescent, deep electronics, backed by a swirl of percussion and an exceptional attention to textural detail? Rolls right off the tongue. At any rate, this headphone-friendly double drop sums the qualities of his best-known projects—2562's swampy low-end, A Made Up Sound's nonlinear jams—in a teeming soundscape with an almost hydraulic sense of progression. "It has a lot of character," he once told us about his gear, "and that's why I like it." Dave, the feeling's mutual.– Gabriel SzatanListen:BandcampTracksTracey"Sex Life"The anonymous London-based duo knocked everyone out of the park with their self-titled debut. Press play once and you'll be convinced. "Sex Life" is deadly dubstep in classic form, with a searing verse from vaunted MC Riko Dan. But then, there's a twist. "Sex Life" also features surprising interludes of twinkling synths and bubblegum vocal loops with a bedroom pop feel—inflections that add a touch of irreverent internet humour. It's a perfect marriage of neon pop and bass weight—a uniquely 2025 take on dubstep.– Nyshka ChandranListen:BandcampLauren Duffus"N.U.M.T.E."Lauren Duffus's Can's Gone Warm EP is her best work yet. On "N.U.M.T.E," fragile, R&B-inflected vocals float over jittery breakbeats and shadowy synths, recalling the likes of Murlo and MssingNo without ever feeling derivative. The track inhabits the liminal space between the club and the lonely hours after closing, leaving a lingering sense of longing wrapped in mystery. It's exactly the kind of idiosyncratic, emotionally vivid production that marked Duffus as one of the year's most compelling artists.– Fahad AkinsanyaListen:BandcampMixBeatrice M.THE DUBSTEP - TECH HOUSE CONNECTIONIn this NTS Radio entry, Beatrice M. explores the connection between two once maligned genres, dubstep and tech house. Joined by Appleblim, they map the sonic bridge from Bristol to Berlin, zeroing in on the collision point where technoid bass hybrids meet skippy 120-BPM rollers—the juncture where Villalobos can bring low-end into his sets or Shackleton can put steppers onto Perlon. All the greats are there: Margaret Dygas, Sub Basics, Pinch, Zenker Brothers. Skankers, wafters, at the end of the day, don't we all bleed bro?– Rachel Grace AlmeidaListen:SoundCloudFurther ListeningSub BasicsNever Too LateListen:BandcampCarrierRhythm ImmortalListen:SpotifySkepta, Fred again.."Victory Lap feat. Neo Electronic PopFrom Ray of Light to BRAT, pop records have long repurposed club culture to delight the masses. But in 2025, a sort of reverse osmosis emerged: cutting-edge producers found new avenu

Neo Electronic PopFrom Ray of Light to BRAT, pop records have long repurposed club culture to delight the masses. But in 2025, a sort of reverse osmosis emerged: cutting-edge producers found new avenues for experimentation in pop's effervescent packaging. From Shanti Celeste's glossy love songs on Romance to Oli XL's K-pop meets IDM on Lick The Lens, there's a clear uptick in the use of radio-ready melodies. In a moment when big-room dance music is more mainstream (and more mind-numbing) than ever, underground artists returned to pop as a point of subversion; a new way to enliven drum & bass, trance and trip-hop without sullying the source material.The relationship between pop and dance music dates back to the '80s, when artists like Boy George and The Human League first conceived of pop as a self-aware art form, not a chart metric. Their vision was fuelled by the same anti-establishment spirit that influenced club innovators like Larry Heard and Underground Resistance. In 2025, pop sounds more in line with that original art punk mentality than it has in decades. There's always been pop worth dancing to, but it's been a long time since so many skilled dance music producers have contributed to the cause.– Hattie LindertRecord of the YearOklouchoke enoughThe off‑centre vaporwave pop songs on Oklou's radical debut make for perfect bedroom music. The French musician's hypnagogic dream logic and tender harmonies render life's most existential moments with microscopic precision and a lulling calm. "endless" opens like a beacon from a far‑off village, her dulcet, auto‑tuned vocals shutting out all notifications from the outside world. "thank you for recording" turns surveillance into a lullaby, while "blade bird" crystallises the album's themes of attachment and harm into weightless nursery rhymes. In the background hum of 2025's global crises, this kind of dissociative dream pop feels spot on, turning panic into an exquisitely arranged experience. This is a record for soft clubbing; for dreamers who want the night to blur rather than explode.– Gio SantiagoRead the full reviewListen:BandcampRecordskeiyaAhooke's lawIt's rare to be transported inside an artist's head. keiyaA's second album is so expressive that listeners can almost hear her neurons crackling as she crafts track after track of achingly intimate music. It's like reading her diary, while also pilfering her drug stash. The Chicago-raised artist translates the chaos of heartbreak, self-doubt, rage and mental illness into a brilliant bricolage of experimental pop and R&B. These 19 cuts are surreal and unsettling, but also raw and truthful, portraying soul music as both escapism and catharsis.– Cameron CookRead the full reviewListen:BandcampPinkPantheressFancy ThatPinkPantheress crashed into 2025 with a mixtape that supercharged the London producer's breakbeat-driven sound. Her recognisable traits—a core palette of UKG, jungle, drum & bass; Y2K-era samples, conversational vocals—remain, but overall, Fancy That is so bold and bright that it feels like a reinvention. Hands-in-the-air moments, faster tempos and peak-time melodies are abundant. With surprise summer hits like the Underworld-sampling "Illegal" and the Groove Armada-inspired "Stateside," the young luminary proved she can go from being an internet star to the leader of club-pop's next generation.– Shaad D'SouzaRead the full reviewListen:SpotifyTracksFKA twigs"Girl Feels Good"Eusexua is all about revelation—the sensation of finding your true self "under a hard metal silver stiletto on the damp rave floor." On "Girl Feels Good," the album's trip-hop highlight, the UK multi-hyphenate celebrates this sentiment with unbridled joy. Over brooding guitar and an entrancing techno-pop chorus, she sings how a woman's blossoming pleasure can fill a night with infinite potential. A proper ode to female desire, this is a song as sacred as it is profane.– Vrinda JagotaRead the full reviewListen:SpotifyRochelle Jordan"Bite The Bait"Rochelle Jordan's sixth album, Through The Wall, served a masterclass in assured and sexy house with a pop sheen. "Bite The Bait," produced by regular collaborator Jimmy Edgar, is a late-night R&B jam where the Chicago artist's teasing, honeyed soprano drips over stripped-back drums."Pulled up to the party it was me, myself and I / Breaking hella hearts I didn't even have to try," she sings, radiating a quiet confidence that carries the track right from the club to the afters at dawn.– Katie ThomasListen:BandcampMixbambinodjLIVE FROM EARTH Mix 79If you've fallen for the hazy alt-pop of Oklou or Malibu, you'll find a kindred spirit in bambinodj. His music welds the Black diasporic sounds of shatta, amapiano and Flex Dance Music with trance, ambient and IDM. These aren't genres that a DJ would typically pair, but in bambinodj's world, it makes perfect sense. This mix encapsulates his sonic DNA: downtempo Balearic haze, inscrutable SoundCloud oddities, Caribbean rhythms and majestic piano leads that put Marc Cohn's Walking in Memphis to shame.– Fahad AkinsanyaListen:SoundCloudFurther ListeningSudan ArchivesThe BPMListen:BandcampJim Legxacyblack british music (2025)Listen:BandcampFcukers"Play Me"Listen:BandcampGeorge Riley"Private Life"Listen:SpotifyMalibuUnited In Flames w/ JAMESJAMESJAMESListen:SoundCloudListen to the Neo Electronic Pop playlistSpotify

Noise DistortionDance music's edges have frayed in fascinating ways in 2025. Whether an attempt to make sense of a world still vibrating with instability, or simply a rejection of the overpolished clu

Noise DistortionDance music's edges have frayed in fascinating ways in 2025. Whether an attempt to make sense of a world still vibrating with instability, or simply a rejection of the overpolished club tools that continue to flood the scene, some of the year's best releases have been forged from the cracks—records that find beauty in disintegration.At the centre of this shift is a renewed fascination with noise and distortion, not only as sonic aesthetic but as emotional language. Disparate artists seem to be drawn to sounds that carry strain, abrasion or a sense of dislocation. Distortion communicates pressure—be that in a personal sense or wider communities navigating upheaval. Even when artists such as Los Thuthanaka or aya pushed their palettes into raw or blown-out territory, it was less about harshness for its own sake and more about revealing what lay beneath the polish.Equally, distortion took on a more introspective bent. Producers working in slower or more reflective modes—Klein, DJ Haram, Rainy Miller—leaned into erosion as a kind of emotional texture. Their use of noise suggested memory slipping, feelings blurring, structures softening rather than breaking.While far from a new phenomenon, perhaps this turn toward noise is a response to an era defined by overstimulation. Amid algorithmic smoothness and endless playlists, distortion feels like something human again. It restores the club's physicality: a reminder that dance music has always thrived on what doesn't quite fit, on frequencies that shake your body as much as they move your feet.– Michael LawsonRecord of the YearLos ThuthanakaLos ThuthanakaUnless you experience synesthesia, listening to Los Thuthanaka might be the closest you'll get to seeing sound. Digitised Andean folk music brings to mind brown mountains and deep blue lakes, while corroded synths are redlined to evoke a radioactive lime green. The first collaborative album from siblings Joshua Crampton and Chuquimamani-Condori melds Andean folk, queer psychedelia and staticky ambient into an ultra-digital experience. Crampton's chugging electric guitar provides the bedrock, setting the atmosphere ablaze while Chuquimamani-Condori gets busy with their sampler, adding bursts of humour via cartoonish, pitched-down voices yelling "Yo!" or "Grrrrr!" over sun-dappled rhythms. These crackling loops become heaving, transcendental waves of sound, haptic feedback sent all the way down from their ancestors.– Kiana MicklesRead the full reviewListen:BandcampRecordsayahexed!Trauma scuffs your spirit, the way an explosion leaves your ears ringing. aya's mesmerising second album seeks to confront her past battles with substance addiction head-on and out loud. The album is rife with one detonation after another, conveying the dark side of the never-ending afters. Muddy digital roar becomes purifying fire; the feedback of a siren's call pulls you in like a friend begging you to party. But listen through to the end of the record, and you'll hear the victorious sound of newfound self-control.– Jesse DorrisRead the full reviewListen:BandcampDJ KRadio Libertadora !On his debut LP, PANICO NO SUBMUNDO, São Paulo producer DJ K made as much noise as possible, defying conservative efforts to silence Brazilian funk with walls of tuin-tinged sub-bass unique to bruxaria, his preferred strain. His second album, Radio Libertadora !, focuses more on favela life and its anarchy. Guitar JamsRight now, guitars are everywhere in electronic music, a reflection of the great blending of genres that's defined the past five years. In 2025, albums were rarely anchored to one sound, of

Guitar JamsRight now, guitars are everywhere in electronic music, a reflection of the great blending of genres that's defined the past five years. In 2025, albums were rarely anchored to one sound, often enlisting the malleable quality of the guitar to transform electronic beats into rock ballads. As one of the oldest instruments, guitars can provoke a jolt of time-worn emotion. That tug on the heart when you hear a lonely minor key? Practically baked into human DNA. Ambling post-rock arpeggios can inspire visions of pastoral terrain, while an indie-pop glissando might give you a new lease of life. Fans clamour to see Smerz's dramatic live rendition of "You got time and I got money," while at home they hit replay for the moping chords that stretch out below the duo's honeyed lyrics.Rock faded out of the mainstream in the late '00s, as EDM, rap and pop surged across the next decade. The genre struggled to reclaim its place in the zeitgeist, until a post-pandemic malaise stalked the music industry and everyone reached for their guitars. Copenhagen—which, in addition to Smerz, is home to Astrid Sonne, ML Buch and Erika de Casier—led the charge. Using the guitar as a textural tool, these artists built layers atop introspective electronic foundations. They bottled a year of political turmoil and economic decline into songs that felt double-sided, capturing a youthful angst alongside a yearning for something, anything, more.– Kiana MicklesRecord of the Yearjames KFriendOn Friend, Jamie Krasner wields her guitar with the freedom of an acrobat flying through the air. Using space to transformative effect, she defies expectations of electronic pop songwriting through her mastery of genre. Wispy tones lap gently against glowing reverbed vocals, bringing an expansive feel to the album's unique strain of ethereality.There's no doubt Krasner can shred in a more classic indie rock vein (see "On God"'s swathes of dream pop chords), but where she really excels is in transforming the guitar altogether through sampling and meticulously applied FX. Whether it's chugging alongside the peppy heartbeat drums on "Play," sputtering over choral vocal samples on the cavernous "Rider" or undulating at the core of trip-hoppy "Blinkmoth (July Mix)," her guitar shapeshifts throughout Friend's electronic landscape as mutably as a synth could.– Sue ParkRead the full reviewListen:BandcampRecordsAcopiaBlush ResponseAcopia's third album is a shimmering haze of shoegaze guitars and soft, yearning vocals. Moving away from the drum programming and grittier, bass-driven sound of previous records, Blush Response revels in downtempo, sparse grooves and cool-headed trip-hop. Vocalist Kate Durman channels her lilting soubrette over distorted fuzz, reverb-laden guitar tones and the wonky harmonics of tracks like "Chase Me" and "Let Down." The album is a dreamlike, wafting soundworld seen through bleary eyes.– Ammar KaliaRead the full reviewListen:BandcampJoanne RobertsonBlurrrIn a year full of albums that sound like they might have drifted from an abandoned campsite, Blurrr distinguishes itself with the subtle spectrum of sound it teases from everyday tools. The UK musician's guitar groans in her hands as much as it sings, always a low, solid counterweight to her floating and translucent voice. This is an album that envelopes you like mist: slowly, imperceptibly, until all of a sudden it's all you can see.– Sasha GeffenRead the full reviewListen:BandcampTracksSmerz"You got time and I got money"On "You got time and I've got money," Smerz cement their claim to Scandi fame. It's the Copenhagen duo's own "Bittersweet Symphony," an orchestral love song that documents the thrill of a new relationship. Although the track's smoky bass guitar plucks a refrain in D minor sharp—the key of mourning—it still lands as a serene dispatch from the honeymoon phase, all warm embraces and waking up together. Over the smoothest drumline of the year, Catharina Stoltenberg and Henriette Motzfeldt wallow in a grounded romance: patient, consistent and built to endure.– Hattie LindertListen:BandcampNourished By Time"Max Potential"The brazen heart of "Max Potential" is riven: between passion and resignation, romance and staying true to oneself. This standout from Nourished By Time's fantastic second album, The Passionate Ones, establishes a remarkable sweep. The Baltimore singer teases out love's inherent freneticism, while the arrangements shift wildly—a frantic dynamic for frantic times. Eventually, the protean musical sensibility whips the urgent central lyric, "If I'm gonna go insane / At least I'm loved by you," into a mantra for the steadfast and enamoured. The effect is irresistible.– Daniel FelsenthalRead the full reviewListen:BandcampMixLogic1000DJ​-​Kicks: Logic1000Conceived as a "little piece of serenity," Logic1000's dreamy, zoned-out mix for !K7's iconic DJ-Kicks series wrapped us in a cocoon, capturing the mood for all things downtempo across a vapour trail of ambient dub, of-the-moment trip-hop and esoteric Scandi pop. Leaning into picks from some of 2025's most talked-about artists—james K, Smerz, Purelink, Oklou, Blood Orange and Yves Tumor—the Australian producer and DJ turned in a guitar-laced tincture of self-care, swapping house bangers for home-listening gems.– April Clare WelshRead the full reviewListen:BandcampFurther ListeningModel / ActrizPirouetteRead the reviewListen:BandcampBlood OrangeEssex HoneyRead the reviewListen:SpotifySaffron Bloom"Flame Never Dies"Listen:BandcampRaisa K"Stay feat. Club HeatersAt the end of every year, we usually identify a single track that seemed to unite every club and festival stage. Think Maya Jane Coles' "What They Say," Kassem Mosse's "Untitled (A1)" or J

Club HeatersAt the end of every year, we usually identify a single track that seemed to unite every club and festival stage. Think Maya Jane Coles' "What They Say," Kassem Mosse's "Untitled (A1)" or Joy Orbison's 2024 smash "flight fm," tracks that sliced clean through our imagined trenches and could make any dance floor move in unison.In 2025, it felt like that moment never quite materialised. Don't get us wrong: the absence of a unanimous dance floor heater doesn't mean there wasn't a slew of excellent club music coming out. It's more that the heat got more localised. It's long been true that what goes off in, say, New York, stands apart from what works in Ibiza, and this year, those differences made the notion of a single, standout club anthem untenable.The lack of universal hits, however, meant more breathing room. This year, the producers soundtracking peak-time moments have stayed small, specific and rooted. For the cohort revelling against AI slop, algorithmic sameness and other homogenising forces, the result was a landscape defined by artistic pluralism and local autonomy rather than one-size-fits-all trends.This shift hints at progress. The appetite for hard and fast persists, sure, but it mutated, shaped by space, crowd and context. Instead of one monolithic sound dominating the scene, you get micro-moments: whether that be the Come Round EP by DJ PGZ & Yikes, two Aboriginal producers staking their claim on the sound of Australian dance floors and bush doofs; or Kiara Scuro and Sugar Free, whose respective releases channelled a sleazy, slow-burning chug familiar to anyone who has clocked in hours at fabric or Houghton. A welcome reminder that the notion of peak time can—and should—offer something different for every floor.– Bella AquilinaRecord of the YearDJ PGZ & YikesCome RoundCome Round has the unbridled energy of a peak-time dance floor coursing through it. Gunai/Kurnai and Yorta Yorta artist DJ PGZ and Boorloo-based Wongi artist Yikes forged their bond in underground spaces—from DJ PGZ attending formative queer parties to inviting Yikes to play his first set at Sub Club in Naarm. Here, that early spark comes full circle. Across solo cuts, cross-remixes and a standout joint track, "Ouss Ouss," the release maps two artists searching for, and ultimately locking into, unity in their respective sounds.It's full throttle from the get‑go: all big, wubby basslines, fierce vocal chops and swirling crescendos that summon the kind of feral inhibition only a grimy basement can unlock. DJ PGZ's pulsing hard techno interlocks with Yikes's spacious, trance-leaning grooves, all threaded by percussive broken beats. The result captures a powerful moment, as two First Nations producers propel Australian dance music into its next chapter.– Hannah DoodyListen:BandcampRecordsKiara ScuroNight Crush​​On Kassian's Rinse FM show in February, Rosie Ama described Night Crush, the debut (and final) Kiara Scuro EP, as "an ode to being on the dance floor when you don't really know what time it is." That disoriented thrill runs through all three tracks: the haziness of heavy reverb and the way the deep, rolling grooves lock your body into the rhythm. Every so often, a repeating riff on opener "Witching Hour" invites that movement, murmuring "body, in motion." File this one with your favourite Planet Euphorique releases.– Katie ThomasListen:BandcampSugar FreeDisociandoJust like her DJ sets, Sugar Free's debut EP squirms with amoebic movement. Disociando's prog house and tech house cuts swell and contract like jellyfish in water, balancing moments of hips-swaying bliss with heads-down enthralment. Pared-back drums add tension and a touch of sleaze, while gorgeous textural details—oddball synth burbles and feedback buildups—bring a zany experimentalism into the mix. This striking amalgam of psychedelia, minimal house and bounce is a peak-time treat with grit and groove, but it's also slinky enough to work the afters.– Nyshka ChandranRead the full reviewListen:BandcampTracksWOST"Banda"Not "banda" as in band, but as in crew. This Spanish translation nails the mantra of the global posse that WOST and Colombian label TraTraTrax have been rallying over the years. On "Banda," the Bogotá-based producer unleashes a percussive cut that's travelled from Video Club to Rinse FM. There's FM synthesis, a drum breakdown and a sped-up dembow tresillo beat so syncopated it sounds like it might mutate into dubstep with each bar. As the gap between the Latin American and UK undergrounds keeps closing, "Banda" proves electronic fusion never has to dilute flavour.– Rachel Grace AlmeidaListen:BandcampJump Source"On (feat. Martyn Bootyspoon)"Patrick Holland and Priori have been quietly producing with other artists—like james K and Physical Therapy—from their Montreal studio. They've still had time to crank out earworms like "On," a euphoric club track so infectious it disarms even the most dedicated techno purists. The confluence of Jump Source's meticulous production and Martyn Bootyspoon's signature vocal swagger is a showcase in style that feels both retro-futurist and viscerally current. In a sense, it's the sound of 2025—a reach for nostalgic sounds that sits undeniably in the present.– Chloe LulaListen:BandcampMixDJ Tobzy Imole GiwaLagos City UnloadedThe algorithm demands bitesized clips of DJs blending belters together. You can either curse this tyranny, or do like DJ Tobzy Imole Giwa does and exaggerate the formula. On Lagos City Unloaded, the cruise beat DJ blitzes through hyperspeed pop, R&B and Eurodance alongside continental genres like Afrobeat, kwaito and amapiano. During one flurry, Lil Wayne's famous "A Milli" a capella creeps in with the subtlety of Looney Tunes's Sylvester before being ousted by the Tweety Bird-pitched trill of Yves Larock's "Rise Up." As DJ Tobzy pushes everything he touches to cartoonish extremes, he makes disparate genres find copious common ground.– Joseph FrancisListen:BandcampFurther ListeningBaaltiMelaRead the reviewListen:BandcampPloyIt's Later Than You ThinkRead the reviewListen:BandcampKhadija Al Hanafi"Bounce It On The Flo"Listen:BandcampJSPORT"No Turning Back"Listen:BandcampKontronatura b2b Nick LeónCarnaval Novo AffairListen:SoundCloudListen to the Club Heaters playlistSpotify

Modern Love

      
        Carrier –
        Rhythm Immortal
      
      
        As a producer, Carrier specialises in white space. On
        Rhythm Immortal, the UK artist's use of percussion is the
        centrepiece, but the gaps he leaves in between the beats are the most
        compelling. Dub techno, ambient, industrial and jazz motifs unite in
        perfect harmony. Just listen to "Offshore," where slithering synths and
        hiccuping drums are tempered by saxophone and piano chords that gleam
        quietly like little spots of sun.

        splits proceeds between the
        Gaza Mutual Aid Solidarity Fund
        and
        NDLON's Immigrant Defense Fund, featuring songs that skitter between ambient, techno and East Coast
        club. Daniel Pineda's "Do Something" captures the sense of urgency
        underlining both politics and dance floors right now. Note the blaring
        siren, club breaks and a voice echoing, "Do something to stop the
        killing."

Shy One
    
      NTS - 100% D'Angelo
    
    
      Few artists have reshaped modern soul as profoundly as D'Angelo. Following his death in October, Shy One offers a heartfelt tribute tracing the arc of his genius, from the church-rooted warmth of Brown Sugar to the fractured funk of Black Messiah. Moving through hits, deep cuts and collaborations, this two-hour mix celebrates an artist who was forever chasing the divine through groove, analogue grit and a one-of-a-kind lyricism.

Mia Koden
    
      Closing Set at Sustain-Release 2025
    
    
      As autumn settles across the northern hemisphere, a wave of festival recordings return to remind us of summer's glow. Among the standouts from this year's romp in Camp Kennybrook is a luminous two-hour journey from Mia Koden, RA's Breaking Through artist of 2024. Rooted in a deep love of Black diasporic music, she moves from dubstep to hip-hop, drifting from Commodo and Daweh Congo to Bahamadia and Minnie Riperton. Sugar Free
    
      Sugar Free at Selectors - Dekmantel 2025
    
    
      A Sugar Free set lands differently. There's a sleazy allure to her take on techno, house and breakbeat, and her vinyl-only sets honour the tradition of the format while always sounding strikingly fresh. The Madrid-based DJ has a knack for uncanny blends: hypnotic grooves meet elastic basslines and trippy, late-night textures weave between deep techno, minimal and psychedelic trance. For her Dekmantel debut, she delivered what she does best: deep, headsy, timeless dance music.

      Live At Dripping

Andy Martin
    
      MNMT 488
    
    
      Listen to any set from Kia, Priori or Cousin and you'll likely hear the dubbed out productions of Mexican-Jamaican producer Andy Martin. Based in Guadalajara, he has become a quiet force in the global underground, uniting sci-fi techno with the rhythmic sensibilities of the Caribbean and Latin America. For Norway's Monument Festival, he delivers a transportive set that moves from the weightless dub pressure of Bukkha and Abstract Man into sleek, hypnotic techno from Oscar Mulero and Unbalance. Here's an hour of music laced with deep bass, subtle psychedelia and shimmering percussive detail.

Scott Zacharias
    
      IT.podcast.s14e07
    
    
      Scott Zacharias has long been one of Detroit's best-kept secrets. His singular, offbeat taste has made his No Way Back sets the stuff of legend. This year's closing in the Outer Space Room was among his most personal yet—as Zacharias recounts in the description, his partner joined him on-stage at the end of the set to celebrate her pregnancy. Anchored by the spirit of Arthur Russell's "In The Light Of The Miracle," the set drifts through everything from cosmic dub and art-pop melancholia to ambient techno and ecstatic house over the course of five hours.

RVNG Intl.
      
        Lucrecia Dalt
        –
        A Danger To Ourselves
      
      
        The past few years have been intense for Lucrecia Dalt. The Colombian
        artist has experienced several seizures and an eight-second stop to her
        heart since her last album, ¡Ay!. She also fell head over heels
        in love. Her latest alt-pop album, A Danger To Ourselves, is
        full-on haunting, as she whispers through a hall of tip-toeing cello and
        guitar plucks. Tracks like "stelliformia" carry the immersive lyricism
        that you'll want to listen to alone in your room.
        A Danger To Ourselves bristles with the kind of eerie love poems
        that only Dalt could write.

        by her Kabyle upbringing surrounded by Algerian chaabi. This is a
        strikingly beautiful portrait of her wispy vocals, which don't need much
        enhancement to make you feel like you've fallen into a world in which
        everything has suddenly and blissfully slowed down.

Tresor
      
        TYGAPAW –
        IMMIGRANT
      
      
        The connection that Jamaican artist TYGAPAW has to their queerness and
        home country is written all across their raucous, politically charged
        techno. On their new EP, IMMIGRANT, they portray the immigrant
        experience in post-Trump America as oppressive and repetitive. "Black
        Trans Masculine Experience" gives the floor to Kings-Lee Rose, who
        discusses the societal isolation of Black trans masculine people before
        a flood of percussion fills the soundscape. In TYGAPAW's hands, deep
        feelings are meant to be released through the hips—you'll hear Jersey
        club, dancehall and techno rhythms skitter across "M32."

Gavsborg
      
        Gavsborg - Kiosk Radio
      
      
        Jamaican dance music producers don't get the same recognition as their
        peers in Detroit, Chicago or Berlin. Hailing from East Kingston,
        Gavsborg carries the torch for this generation. The Berlin-based
        Equiknoxx founder has spent more than a decade reshaping dancehall with
        a leftfield sensibility—first breaking through with Busy Signal's
        charting single, "Step Out," before collaborating with everyone from
        reggae dub prince Addis Pablo to hip-hop icon Missy Elliott. On
        Brussels'
        Kiosk Radio,
        Gavsborg dropped a scorching mix of dancehall, jungle, zouk and dub,
        laced with the playful surrealism that defines his productions.

Short Span (Matthew Kent)
      
        Short Span - Theory Therapy 82
      
      
        Across its eight-year run,
        Blowing Up The Workshop
        tested the limits of the online mix format, giving artists space to
        experiment and shaping a generation of adventurous listeners along the
        way. That same curatorial spirit runs through this new Theory Therapy
        session, which sees BUTW founder Matthew Kent digging into forgotten
        '00s CDs to piece together a loose set of dubbed-out ambient and
        downtempo house, with plenty of clicky percussion reminiscent of
        minimal's dominant era.

Keanu Nelson
      
        Keanu Nelson - NTS Radio (13th September 2025)
      
      
        Broadcasting from Papunya, one of Australia's most isolated communities,
        Luritja artist Keanu Nelson offers a rare window into the music and
        voices of the Northwestern territory. For his latest NTS Radio show, he
        drifts from ancestral chants and spectral atmospheres to desert rock and
        jazzy synth pop. The mix moves gracefully between the celebratory and
        the contemplative, its remarkable range making for a perfect morning
        listen.

        love, loneliness and late-stage capitalism over an impeccable blend of
        electro funk and breezy indie pop. Its soulful sound, driven by cruising
        guitars and euphoric synths, buffs up his candid lyrics, making his
        verses (which channel the extreme honesty of 2013-era Tyler, the

Agonis
      
        Animix One Hundred & Seventy Nine: Agonis
      
      
        Basel's amenthia recordings may have carved out a niche with its
        leftfield, slow-burning techno, but label cofounder Agonis shows the
        vibes needn't be austere. Here, the Swiss DJ and producer delivers 66
        minutes of colour and warmth for Kia's beloved
        Animalia series. Groovy, trippy selections are threaded with
        vocals and trance flourishes. It's a reminder that hypnotic techno can
        move with both depth and vibrancy, balancing ritual intensity with
        playful, body-driven momentum.

GQOM MIX TAPES E67 | AUGUST 2025 w/ MAMTHUG

Mamthug
      
        GQOM MIX TAPES E67 | AUGUST 2025 w/ MAMTHUG
      
      
        "Archiving gqom, one mix at a time," reads the tagline for Oroko Radio
        resident Mamthug's GQOM MIX TAPES series. Emerging from Durban's
        townships in the early 2010s, gqom quickly became one of South Africa's
        most influential party genres, defined by heavy bass, stripped-back
        percussion and a brooding intensity. On this episode, Mamthug—usually
        drawn to jazzy breakbeats—leans fully into gqom's vast spectrum, moving
        from sensual cuts to sub-rattling bangers, highlighting both the
        intimacy and force of a genre that remains as vital as ever.

        Transmissions 001: Sunju Hargun
      
      
        Transmissions, the excellent London party spotlighting psychedelic club
        music, books hypnotic techno experimentalists such as DJ Nobu, Polygonia
        and Donato Dozzy. For those unable to attend the raves IRL, the crew has
        started a new mix series, launching with Bangkok-based DJ and label
        owner Sunju Hargun. A recording from FOLD's cosier second space, the
        Steam Room, the session opens with ceremonial chants. Vocals twirl
        around body-rattling bass and eerie synth lines, eventually giving way
        to two hours of Hargun's unique take on trippy techno.

In Focus: DJ Medhi (mixed by Antonine Scali)

DJ Mehdi,
      Antoine Scali
      
        In Focus: DJ Medhi (mixed by Antonine Scali)
      
      
        NTS Radio's latest In Focus celebrates DJ Mehdi, a
        hip-hop-kid-turned-house-DJ who defined a generation of Paris nightlife
        in the early 2000s. Raised on the outskirts of the French capital by
        Tunisian parents, he began producing mixtapes and beats inspired by J
        Dilla, before emerging as an unlikely icon of the Paris party scene. His
        radiant selections helped stitch together disparate worlds, from Daft
        Punk and Justice to MC Solaar. This hour-long mix captures that alchemy:
        rugged, sample-heavy productions for 113, Rohff and Mafia K'1 Fry sit
        alongside glossy, synth-driven anthems like "Pocket Piano," culminating
        in the euphoric climax of Thomas Bangalter's edit of "Signatune."

        Mbizo spins an hour of his own productions for Strøm Festival,

Artificial Pinearch Manufacturing

      
        Stars of the Lid
        –
        Music for Nitrous Oxide
      
      
        Stars of the Lid's 1995 debut album is regarded as a classic within the
        ambient and drone world for a reason. The record is dense enough to wrap
        around and colour an environment, but never too imposing. This
        30th-anniversary reissue highlights the pioneering drone duo's staying
        power. The smudged guitar flickers on "Down" gently speak to the current
        moment. In the era of Spotify's anodyne functionality playlists, the
        majesty of a slowly undulating drone piece like "Goodnight" feels like a
        brilliantly comical riposte to the idea of easy-listening music. But
        those subtle challenges have guided Stars of the Lid from the beginning.

        flies between flangered chords and woody percussion.

Neffa-T

      
        8 Deck Technical Mix
      
      
        Neffa-T's 8 Deck Technical Mix is a stunning showcase of the
        continued potential of mixing records. Never one to rest on his laurels,
        the CDJ wizard's latest filmed session is 80 minutes of jaw-dropping
        skill. More than just a numbers stunt, his use of eight decks and two
        mixers allows for razor-sharp cuts and the spontaneous recomposition of
        tracks in real time, blurring the line between DJing and live
        performance. Almost constantly moving, it's as transfixing to watch as
        it is to listen to. Much like Jeff Mills' seminal
        Exhibitionist
        series, this is a vulnerable, high-wire act of solo mastery that will be
        talked about for years. Just remember the popcorn.

Dave Huismans (AKA A Made Up Sound)

      
        Hessle Audio - 30 June 2025
      
      
        "It's experimental music that people have to move to." So
        said
        Ben UFO back in 2016 when reflecting on A Made Up Sound's unique appeal.
        For a decade, the musician's catalogue was home to a wild alchemy of
        sounds—take "Afterhours," a lurching, 12-minute hybrid of dubstep and
        Detroit techno—that inspired total awe in his contemporaries. Though the
        Dutch producer has kept a low profile in recent years, his latest
        project, ex_libris, proves that his guiding ethos of innovation has only
        deepened. His two-hour Hessle Audio takeover, which explores a range of
        personal favourites and early influences (Mary J. Blige, Krust), is a
        markedly intimate offering from an artist who's long thrived on bending
        boundaries in every direction.

        Loidis has an uncanny ear for deep tech house gems, the kind with

Moopie

      
        Timeless Series #52
      
      
        This ambient and downtempo session is a mental massage for knotty
        thoughts. Ethereal pads, lush soundscapes and nature noises (frog
        ribbits, the plink of water droplets) seem to capture a time-lapse of a
        tropical ecosystem. Over the rhythmic chug of distorted synth lines,
        hissing melodies and barely there vocal samples, Moopie soundtracks a
        rainforest in transition, taking listeners across the seasons. It's an
        hour of pure, contemplative bliss—and a critical ear cleanse.

james K

      
        Truancy Volume 353
      
      
        In the hands of james K, music becomes emotional architecture. Layering
        melancholy, surrender and longing alongside murkier feelings such as
        anxiety, the New York-based artist builds sets like an urban planner of
        the heart. This 74-minute trek across mediative downtempo, drum & bass
        and sample-based experimentalism finds through lines between artists on
        the opposite sides of the dance music spectrum, from the delicate piano
        notes of Tristan Arp to Marco Shuttle's quiet percussion. It ends on a
        bittersweet note with the IDM pop of Cybermission's "Deep Hard," which
        james K
        described
        as her "current favourite feeling" because "it's fun, beautiful and
        real."

        production. The resulting LP is multitudinal: tactile and knotty yet
        fluid and trance-like, offering all the forward-looking potential of

        DJ Bone –

        In late May, DJ Bone decided to put out a whopping six releases to
        celebrate his accomplishments: five years of his FURTHER label, 30 years
        of his Subject Detroit label, 35 years in the music industry and, most
        importantly, his 55th birthday.

        his previous LPs, crackling with the futurism and thrust of the best
        Detroit techno. Take "Critical," which consists of little more than
        drums, a squelchy, two-chord Juno stab and hip-hop-coded vocals. It
        feels like mainlining a double espresso.

        When Joan Didion set her sights on Miami during its mid-'80s heyday, she
        looked past the pastel-hued condos to find a new form of hybridised
        decay—attempts to mask state-sanctioned corruption behind the veneer of
        a tropical paradise. It's an unexpected yet totally apt point of
        reference for Nick León, a proud ambassador of Miami's dance music
        scene. But A Tropical Entropy is far from a dour outing. "Ocean
        Apart," for instance, almost becomes a full-blown EDM rager, but backs
        away before the catharsis of a major drop.

        through the past two decades of dance music—from French touch to
        dubstep, hip-hop to deconstructed club—stitched over erratic drum
        programming and imbued with bloghouse's cocaine-fueled irreverence.

Oceanic at Garage, Horst Arts & Music 2025

Oceanic

      
        Oceanic at Garage, Horst Arts & Music 2025
      
      
        One of the most memorable sets at this year's Horst Arts & Music wasn't
        on the festival's main stage, but its most intimate. In a low-lit corner
        of Garage, Oceanic delved into the wonky side of house music—strange
        vocals, minimal classics and beatless synth workouts. Featuring Laurie
        Spiegel and Skee Mask, the two-and-a-half-hour recording is melodic and
        weightless in parts, heavy and heady in others—but consistently
        elevating.

Everything reminds me of dubstep pt. III - curated by livwutang

livwutang,
      Beatrice M.

      
        Everything reminds me of dubstep pt. III - curated by livwutang
      
      
        Everything reminds me of dubstep is a series that reimagines the UK-born
        genre through its softest moments—the bridges, outros and tender
        undercurrents. For the third instalment, New York-based DJ (and former
        Resident Advisor staffer) livwutang curates a playlist which
        Beatrice M. then assembled into a mix that foregrounds lush, sweeping
        melodies and emotional density. It's a love letter to the genre's
        range—a reminder that dubstep has always been just as much about feeling
        as force.

        Set in the lush surroundings of Buritaca, Colombia, Bonanza Festival has
        quietly become a key meeting point for Latin America's electronic
        community. Adi, born in Bogotá and now based in Brussels, has built a
        steady following for her blends of trippy house, electro and techno,
        tinged with acid. Taking over from Nicolas Lutz at 7:30 AM, she kept up
        the momentum with nimble rhythms and just the right amount of sleaze,
        squelch and restraint.

BMG

      
        IT.podcast.s14e04: BMG at No Way Back 2025
      
      
        If Detroit's Movement Festival is a pilgrimage, then No Way Back is its
        sacred ritual. The annual Tangent Gallery gathering is special for
        everyone involved, chiefly the DJs, who always go the extra mile. Motor
        City legend BMG is no exception. This year, he debuted fresh hardware
        remasters and exclusive edits of Pink Floyd, 808 State and Aphex Twin,
        alongside forthcoming releases on Interdimensional Transmissions. As he
        said himself: "We start at the Tangent and end up travelling to the
        other side of the universe."

        anguished indie a la Bar Italia ("Take Care"). The style experiments

        On Revengeseekerz, Jane Remover's surprise third record, they
        race through their earliest, long-abandoned digicore work with newfound
        dexterity. Noise columns meet otherworldly, loosely stacked guitar
        notes. Standout "Professional Vengeance" could've been a Pixies song in
        another life, if the group played so hard and fast that the studio
        imploded. At their best, these songs join traditional emo with overblown
        electronics so seamlessly that you forget the American musician once
        debated choosing between the two.

        York musicality of "Sax and Drugs;" springy prog-house on "Thisiz House
        Music," reminiscent of the '00s Melbourne scene; and the effusive
        positivity of the title track, which channels the energy of Eris Drew's
        Motherbeat philosophy.

        closer: "No Genre, Only Music."

        Hieroglyphic Being

        Chicago producer Hieroglyphic Being has been partying for a long time.
        "40 years later," he said about the club scene in
        Dance Music 4 Bad People's liner notes, "it's drastically
        different—everybody's angry!" His latest album is an attempt to change
        that. In the distorted, crunchy haze that typically defines his music,
        he brings out funky, wayward synth lines and drums. This is the kind of
        adventurous house that only Hieroglyphic Being can create, with each
        delightfully strange track centred around a perfect loop.

        Ploy –

        London-based producer Ploy has consistently put out bassy, percussive
        dance music that many now think of as "UK techno." But on new album,
        It's Later Than You Think, he makes a hard left turn to take on
        the vast spectrum of house. There's the hardgroove-meets-house of
        "Admirer," and "Monsters," a throwback to the early-'90s drum work of DJ
        Pierre and Zip's '00s minimal. "Stringz" balances the old and new Ploy:
        mixing his new love of hard house with wormhole techno.

Temporal Drift
      
        Hiroshi Yoshimura –
        Flora
      
      
        Hiroshi Yoshimura was a revered figure in
        kankyō ongaku,
        Japan's environmental music scene, known for creating artfully
        unobtrusive works like Surround and the seminal
        Music for Nine Post Cards. This posthumous album offers a fresh perspective on a musician best
        known for meditative atmospherics. In contrast to the quiet subtleties
        of his early records, tracks like "Maple Syrup Factory" sound like
        Yoshimura's equivalent of a pop song. Bouncy and engaging,
        Flora's playful pace actively asks for your focus.

Hyperdub
      
        aya –
        hexed!
      
      
        The cosmic darkness of
        aya's debut
        album, im hole, is best captured by its lead single, "Emley
        lights us moor." The song is terrifying, comprising macabre field
        recordings and uneasy synths that soundtrack a mind seemingly caught
        between psychosis and epiphany. Three years on, the most surprising
        aspect of aya's follow-up, hexed!, is just how deliberately it
        functions as a sequel: eerie spoken-word morphs into screams, while
        drums and lasers clatter together relentlessly. On hexed!, she
        draws from metalcore, IDM and hardstyle, ditching cloistered inwardness
        for a cathartic expulsion of energy.

Unspecified Enemies –
        Romance in the Age of Adaptive Feedback

Numbers.
      
        Unspecified Enemies –
        Romance in the Age of Adaptive Feedback
      
      
        Louis Digital—AKA Unspecified Enemies—has always looked ahead with a
        cynical eye. His scattered discography often references the late urban
        theorist Mike Davis, namechecking his interrogations of systems of
        power, explored in books like City of Quartz and
        Ecology of Fear. Louis Digital moulded the first Unspecified
        Enemies album from puzzle pieces of synths, samples and sequences made
        in the early '00s. Romance in the Age of Adaptive Feedback flips
        Davis's pessimism to transmit the hopeful mood of the new millennium.

        the actual '90s—a quick excerpt from Dettinger's 1999 ambient pop
        touchstone Intershop, the intro to Wamdue Kids' 1996 deep house
        LP These Branching Moments—knit into contemporary Y2K throwbacks,
        like the smouldering trip-hop of a.s.o.'s "Somebody" and the ethereal
        downtempo of Moon Holiday's "Definitely."

Self-released
      
        MoMA Ready
        –
        MR001
      
      
        The agenda of MoMA Ready's first record of 2025? Gritty, romantic house.
        The New York producer leaves behind samples to put his own words front
        and centre, bringing earnest poetry to songs like "Suddenly," where love
        begets feelings of self-acceptance ("I feel like I belong / And there's
        nothing wrong"). The emotional tone of the EP—and the ecstasy it chases
        after—is no less driving than his peak-time anthems. On "Feel Like
        That," over a nasty bassline that slithers close to the floor, he asks,
        "How do you feel?"

Jlin Metalabel
      
        Jlin –
        B12
      
      
        Sydney's Powerhouse Museum is home to half a million objects. Its new
        initiative, Sounding the Collection, allows musicians to access
        this archive and use samples recorded at the museum to create their own
        original musical responses. On B12, Jlin makes use of a talking
        robot, an Irish harp and a wire-tying machine, with hazy melodies
        grounding the rhythmic chaos. This might just be the closest thing to
        hip-hop she's worked on in recent years.

Beatrice M.
        &
        Appleblim
      
      
        The Dubstep-Tech House Connection
      
      
        The Paris-based BAIT label boss
        Beatrice M.
        has emerged as a key figure in reshaping dubstep in the 2020s, picking
        up where pioneers like Peverelist and Pinch left off. Their fascination
        with "techy" dubstep and the history of crossover sounds, dating back to
        the early 2000s, informs this NTS Radio broadcast, which is part mix,
        part talk show. Beatrice M. blends tracks with insights from Appleblim,
        and discusses the genre's evolution from dubstep's deeper, soulful roots
        to its influence on minimal and tech house.

Young
      
        FKA Twigs
        –
        Eusexua
      
      
        FKA twigs shines with a quality we haven't really seen before on her
        third studio album, Eusexua. Anchoring her songwriting in the canon of
        '90s dance music, she draws from trip-hop, IDM, electro and living room
        techno, though the LP's best moments reference the darkness of the club.
        While the LP is a response to the liberating euphoria she has
        experienced on the dance floor, the music is no less cerebral than on
        revered full-lengths
        Magdalene
        and
        LP1. There's a gripping seriousness about her devotion to pleasure across
        the album, from the trip-hop poetry on "Girl Feels Good" to the operatic
        runs on "Striptease."

Driving trance and techno that sound like the space between sapphic ecstasy and delirium.
